e for publishing blog posts: gatsby-theme-blog. This plugin bundles multiple features, such as MDX support and code highlighting, into one convenient package. Throughout the tutorial, you will follow the process of using this specific Gatsby theme, which you can then apply to themes in general."), mdx("p", null, "Each step will take you through an important part of using Gatsby themes, and by the end you will have seen how this process can be applied to any Gatsby theme that you might want to use in the future."), mdx("p", null, "Prerequisites\nBefore starting, here are a few things you will need:"), mdx("p", null, "A local installation of Node.js for running Gatsby and building your site. The installation procedure varies by operating system, but DigitalOcean has guides for Ubuntu 20.04 and macOS, and you can always find the latest release on the official Node.js download page.\nSome familiarity with JavaScript, for working in Gatsby. The JavaScript language is an expansive topic, but a good starting point is our How To Code in JavaScript series.\nA new Gatsby project, scaffolded from gatsby-starter-default. To build a new Gatsby project from scratch, you can refer to Step 1 of the How To Set Up Your First Gatsby Website tutorial.\nThis tutorial was tested on Node.js v14.16.1, npm v6.14.12, Gatsby v3.11.1, and gatsby-theme-blog v3.0.0."), mdx("p", null, "Step 1 \u2014 Finding and Installing a Theme\nAlthough this tutorial will walk you through using a specific theme, gatsby-theme-blog, each step also applies conceptually to Gatsby themes in general. This applies to this first step as well: finding a theme you wish to use and installing it with npm."), mdx("p", null, "Gatsby provides guidance to plugin and theme authors on how they should publish their Gatsby packages, which makes it easier to find a theme to fit your needs. Theme developers are instructed to tag their theme packages with both gatsby and gatsby-theme as keywords, which are then scanned by package re